on |publisher=Longman |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0582438064 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |title=The European Witch-Craze of the Sixteenth and Seventeenth Centuries and Other Essays |last=Trevor-Roper |first=Hugh |authorlink=Hugh Trevor-Roper |year=1969 |publisher=Harper & Row |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Wilby |first=Emma |authorlink=Emma Wilby |title=[[Cunning Folk and Familiar Spirits|Cunning Folk and Familiar Spirits: Shamanistic Visionary Traditions in Early Modern British Witchcraft and Magic]] |publisher=Sussex Academic Press |location=Brighton |year=2005 |isbn=978-1-84519-078-1 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title= Magic and Superstition in Europe: A Concise History from Antiquity to the Present |last= Bailey, Michael D. |year= 2006 |publisher= Rowman & Littlefield |isbn= 978-0-7425-3386-8 |ref= Bai06 |url= https://archive.org/details/magicsuperstitio00bail }}\n* [[Brian P. Levack|Levack, Brian P]]. ed. ''The Oxford Handbook of Witchcraft in Early Modern Europe and Colonial America'' (2013) [https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0199578168/ excerpt and text search]\n* {{cite news |title= Recent Developments in the Study of the Great European Witch Hunt |last= Gibbons, Jenny   |year= 1998 |journal= The Pomegranate: The International Journal of Pagan Studies |volume=5 |ref=Gib98}}\n* Gouges, Linnea de (2018) ''Witch hunts and State Building in Early Modern Europe'' \n* {{cite book |title= Gerald Gardner and the Cauldron of Inspiration: An Investigation into the Sources of Gardnerian Witchcraft |last= [[Philip Heselton|Heselton, Philip]]   |year= 2004 |publisher= Capall Bann |location= Somerset |ref=Hes04}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.summerlands.com/crossroads/remembrance/_remembrance/stages_witch_trial.htm The Stages of a Witch Trial]\u2014a series of articles by Jenny Gibbons.\n* [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/15674a.htm 1913 ''Catholic Encyclopedia'' entry on \"Witchcraft\"]. Retrieved April 2011\n* [http://www.bede.org.uk/decline.htm The Decline and End of Witch Trials in Europe] by James Hannam\n* [http://www.shc.ed.ac.uk/Research/witches/introduction.html Research on witch trials in Scotland]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p004y2b0 Witchcraft], BBC Radio 4 discussion with Alison Rowlands, Lyndal Roper & Malcolm Gaskill (''In Our Time'', 21 October 2004)\n\n{{Witch Hunt}}\n{{Violence against women/end}}\n\n[[Category:Christianity in the early modern period]]\n[[Category:Early Modern period]]\n[[Category:Early Modern witch hunts|*]]\n[[Category:Magic (supernatural)]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft|Trials in the early modern period]]\n[[Category:Witch trials|*]]\n", "name_user": "82.26.195.113", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(How to spot a which and the crew punishments)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch_trials_in_the_early_modern_period"}
{"title_page": "Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction", "text_new": "{{short description|British hard rock group}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2012}}\n{{Fan POV|date=November 2019}}}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction\n| image            = Zodiac Lamour.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Zodiac Mindwarp on stage at L'Amour in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], circa 1989\n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hard rock]]\n| years_active     = 1985\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| current_members  = Zodiac Mindwarp<br/>Cobalt Stargazer<br/>Jack Shitt<br/>Bruno 'The Cat' Agua\n| past_members     = [[Jimmy Cauty]]<br/>[[Kid Chaos]]<br/>Boom Boom Kaboomski<br/>Jake Le Mesurier<br/>Slam Thunderhide<br/>Evil Bastard<br/>Trash D Garbage<br/>Flash Bastard<br/>Suzi X<br/>Tex Diablo<br/>Robbie Vom<br/>Kev Reverb<br/>The Apocalypse\n}}\n\n'''Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction''' are a [[British people|British]] [[hard rock]] group, which was formed in 1985.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Guinness Who\u2019s Who of Heavy Metal]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|date=1995|edition=Second|isbn=0-85112-656-1|pages=395/7}}</ref>\n\nZodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction play a sleazy style of commercial [[hard rock]] featuring big [[riff]]s and [[refrain|chorus]]es, as was the trend in the band's heyday of the mid-to-late 1980s and early 1990s. The [[camp (style)|camp]] [[lyrics]] are intended as self-parody, and can be seen as either humorous, or offensive by those who take them at face value, for their often [[lascivious]] and [[misogyny|misogynist]] tone. Song titles like \"Back Seat Education\", \"[[Feed My Frankenstein]]\", \"High Heeled Heaven\", and \"Trash Madonna\" illustrate Mindwarp's tongue-in-cheek approach. Lyrical content also exhibits a send up of [[cult]] [[worship]], often of Zodiac Mindwarp's self-proclaimed raging [[libido]], with Mindwarp claiming the titles 'Sex Fuhrer', 'Love Dictator', and 'High Priest of Love'.\n\n==Overview==\nThe [[band (music)#Rock and pop bands|band]] is the brainchild of Mark Manning, a former [[graphic designer|graphic artist]]<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> and art editor of the now defunct ''[[Flexipop|Flexipop!]]'' magazine. The magazine folded back in 1982 but the hedonistic lifestyle of the frequenting rock and pop stars to the magazine' offices fueled his desire to experience the debauchery of life as a decadent [[rock music|rock]] star. He joined another music publication called ''Metal Fury'' as a graphic designer but assumed the alter ego 'Zodiac Mindwarp' at night. 'Zodiac Mindwarp' was the namesake of a series of underground comics written and illustrated by Spain Rodriquez. Zodiac soon left Metal Fury and formed the Love Reaction in 1985 with [[Jimmy Cauty]] (who later formed [[The Orb]], [[The Justified Ancients of Mu Mu]] and [[The KLF]]) on guitar; [[Kid Chaos]] (real name Stephen Harris) on bass; and Boom Boom Kaboomski on drums.\n\nThe band was signed to the Food label of Phonogram Records who soon issued their first recording, \"Wild Child\" with just Zodiac (playing guitar and vocals), Kid Chaos on bass and Jake Le Mesurier on drums. A demo version of \"High Priest of Love\" was included on the ''[[Melody Maker]]'' ''Vinyl Conflict 2'' free EP in September 1986. By the end of the year the lineup had changed again to accommodate the still present figure of Cobalt Stargazer (real name Geoff Bird) and new drummer Slam Thunderhide (real name Stephen Landrum). That lineup contributed the studio track, \"Drug Shoes,\" to the FOOD ''Imminent 2'' various artists compilation.\n\nAt various times, the band has also featured Evil Bastard (real name Robert Munro who co-penned and sang on two [[A-side and B-side|B-sides]]: \"Hangover from Hell\" and \"Lager Woman from Hell\"), Heavy Metal Bear (real name Alex Bradly), Trash D Garbage (real name Paul Bailey), Flash Bastard (real name Jan Cyrka), Suzi X (real name Richard Levy), Tex Diablo (real name Christopher Renshaw), and Robbie Vom (real name Rob Morris).\n\nZodiac Mindwarp progressed rapidly from their first gig at [[Dingwalls]] in November 1985, to playing in front of a packed [[Reading Festival]] in 1986, but was followed by the departure of Kid Chaos who joined [[The Cult]]. Zodiac regrouped by assigning Trash D Garbage on Bass and Flash Bastard (Jan Cyrka) on rhythm guitar section. The expanded five member outfit all went on to record Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction's debut album in 1988 entitled ''[[Tattooed Beat Messiah]]''.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> Other band members playing bass include Suzi X, Tex Diablo and Kev Reverb; whilst previous drummers were Robbie Vomm and The Apocalypse.\n\nThe act produced a [[UK Singles Chart]] Top 20 hit with the breakthrough [[Gramophone record|record]] \"Prime Mover\",<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> a song that was inspired musically by [[Hawkwind]]'s 1977 track \"[[Quark, Strangeness and Charm (song)|Quark, Strangeness and Charm]]\", itself heavily inspired by the German group [[NEU!]]{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nThey toured the US supporting [[Alice Cooper]] and  [[Guns N' Roses]] on dozens of dates in 1988. After a few gigs, they were moved up to the middle of the bill between Cooper and Guns N' Roses. Stargazer, Thunderhide and Bastard were also featured in the film ''[[The Decline of Western Civilization Part II: The Metal Years]]'' performing with Slash and Axl Rose (from Guns N' Roses) and Alice Cooper, in an encore from this tour featuring Cooper's hit \"Under My Wheels\". The Love Reaction's 1987 album ''Tattooed Beat Messiah'' failed to sell well enough in the States, resulting in them being dropped by their record label with outstanding debts, according to Zodiac himself.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} The ''Tattooed Beat Messiah'' LP spawned five videos that received regular rotation on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Headbangers Ball]]''.\n\nOccasionally referred to as \"biker rock\", the band's style of hard rock is reflected in their outlandish attire, which tends to parody the post-apocalyptic [[Mad Max (franchise)|Mad Max]] biker look. [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] declared them to be their favourite band and immediately restyled themselves for the ''[[Girls, Girls, Girls (M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce album)|Girls, Girls, Girls]]'' record.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nThey adopted a more common \"street look\", circa their comeback, around 1999.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn recent years, Manning has established himself as an author, penning ''A Bible of Dreams'' (1994) and ''Bad Wisdom'' (1996, both [[Bill Drummond]]); plus ''Crucify Me Again'' (2000), ''Get Your Cock Out'' (2000), ''Fucked by Rock'' (2001), ''Collateral Damage'', and ''The Wild Highway'' (2005, again with Drummond). Manning is also a regular contributor to ''[[The Idler (1993)|The Idler]]'' magazine.\n\n==Notable collaborations==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=November 2019}}\n* Mindwarp co-wrote the track \"There's a Barbarian in the Back of My Car\" on the [[Voice of the Beehive]] album, ''Let It Bee''.\n* He also wrote the track \"Feed My Frankenstein\" which was covered on the [[Alice Cooper]] album, ''[[Hey Stoopid]]''.  Due to Alice changing a small number of the lyrics for his version, he is listed as co-writer. Zodiac Mindwarp and The Love Reaction's own version of the song appeared on their album ''Hoodlum Thunder''.\n* In 1992, Mindwarp appeared on the album ''[[456 (album)|456]]'' by [[The Grid]], performing [[lead vocalist|lead vocals]] on the track \"Fire Engine Red\". Love Reaction guitarist Cobalt Stargazer also appeared on the album, performing on the tracks \"Face the Sun\" and \"Leave Your Body\".\n* The Love Reaction once appeared as [[Belinda Carlisle]]'s (mimed) backing band at a late 1980s/early 1990s award show for the song \"[[Leave a Light On (Belinda Carlisle song)|Leave a Light On]]\".\n\n==Discography==\n===Singles and EPs===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"30\"|\n!width=\"30\"|'''Year'''\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|'''Title'''\n!width=\"70\"|'''<small>[[UK Indie Chart]] Position</small>'''<ref name=\"Lazell\">{{cite book| last = Lazell| first = Barry| title = Indie Hits 1980 to 1989 ; the Complete UK Independent Charts| year = 2002| isbn = 978-0-9517206-9-1| page = 265 }}</ref>\n!width=\"70\"|'''<small>[[UK Singles Chart]] Position</small>'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/24183/zodiac-mindwarp-and-the-love-reaction/|title=ZODIAC MINDWARP & THE LOVE REACTION &#124; full Official Chart History &#124; Official Charts Company|website=Officialcharts.com|accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|May\n|1986\n|\"[[Zodiac Mindwarp Wild Child|Wild Child]]\" EP\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|&ndash;\n|-\n|August\n|1986\n|\"[[Zodiac Mindwarp High Priest Of Love|High Priest of Love]]\" EP\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|&ndash;\n|-\n|May\n|1987\n|\"Prime Mover\"\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|November\n|1987\n|\"Back Seat Education\"\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|&ndash;\n|-\n|April\n|1988\n|\"Planet Girl\"\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|63\n|-\n|\n|1993\n|\"[[Zodiac Mindwarp My Life Story|My Life Story]]\" EP\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|&ndash;\n|}\n\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Tattooed Beat Messiah]]'' (1988) &ndash; [[UK Albums Chart|UK]] No. 20 (re-released in 1997 as ''The Best of Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction'')\n* ''[[Hoodlum Thunder]]'' (1991)\n* ''Live at Reading'' (1993)\n* ''One More Knife'' (1994)\n* ''I Am Rock'' (2002) &ndash; (re-released in 2005 with four demo bonus tracks)\n* ''Weapons of Mass Destruction'' (live album) (2004)\n* ''Rock Savage'' (2005)\n* ''Pandora's Grisly Handbag'' (1986 live album and DVD) (2006)\n* ''[[We Are Volsung]]'' (2010)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.zodiacmindwarp.com/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zodiac Mindwarp}}\n[[Category:1985 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English hard rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Vertigo Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British hard rock group}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2012}}\n{{Fan POV|date=November 2019}}}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction\n| image            = Zodiac Lamour.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Zodiac Mindwarp on stage at L'Amour in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], circa 1989\n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hard rock]]\n| years_active     = 1985\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| current_members  = Zodiac Mindwarp<br/>Cobalt Stargazer<br/>Jack Shitt<br/>Bruno 'The Cat' Agua\n| past_members     = [[Jimmy Cauty]]<br/>[[Kid Chaos]]<br/>Boom Boom Kaboomski<br/>Jake Le Mesurier<br/>Slam Thunderhide<br/>Evil Bastard<br/>Trash D Garbage<br/>Flash Bastard<br/>Suzi X<br/>Tex Diablo<br/>Robbie Vom<br/>Kev Reverb<br/>The Apocalypse\n}}\n\n'''Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction''' are a [[British people|British]] [[hard rock]] group, which was formed in 1985.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Guinness Who\u2019s Who of Heavy Metal]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|date=1995|edition=Second|isbn=0-85112-656-1|pages=395/7}}</ref>\n\nZodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction play a sleazy style of commercial [[hard rock]] featuring big [[riff]]s and [[refrain|chorus]]es, as was the trend in the band\u2019s heyday of the mid-to-late 1980s and early 1990s. The [[camp (style)|camp]] [[lyrics]] are intended as self-parody, and can be seen as either humorous, or offensive by those who take them at face value, for their often [[lascivious]] and [[misogyny|misogynist]] tone. Song titles like \"Back Seat Education\", \"[[Feed My Frankenstein]]\", \"High Heeled Heaven\", and \"Trash Madonna\" illustrate Mindwarp's tongue-in-cheek approach. Lyrical content also exhibits a send up of [[cult]] [[worship]], often of Zodiac Mindwarp's self-proclaimed raging [[libido]], with Mindwarp claiming the titles 'Sex Fuhrer', 'Love Dictator', and 'High Priest of Love'.\n\n==Overview==\nThe [[band (music)#Rock and pop bands|band]] is the brainchild of Mark Manning, a former [[graphic designer|graphic artist]]<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> and art editor of the now defunct ''[[Flexipop|Flexipop!]]'' magazine. The magazine folded back in 1982 but the hedonistic lifestyle of the frequenting rock and pop stars to the magazine' offices fueled his desire to experience the debauchery of life as a decadent [[rock music|rock]] star. He joined another music publication called ''Metal Fury'' as a graphic designer but assumed the alter ego 'Zodiac Mindwarp' at night. 'Zodiac Mindwarp' was the namesake of a series of underground comics written and illustrated by Spain Rodriquez. Zodiac soon left Metal Fury and formed the Love Reaction in 1985 with [[Jimmy Cauty]] (who later formed [[The Orb]], [[The Justified Ancients of Mu Mu]] and [[The KLF]]) on guitar; [[Kid Chaos]] (real name Stephen Harris) on bass; and Boom Boom Kaboomski on drums.\n\nThe band was signed to the Food label of Phonogram Records who soon issued their first recording, \"Wild Child\" with just Zodiac (playing guitar and vocals), Kid Chaos on bass and Jake Le Mesurier on drums. A demo version of \"High Priest of Love\" was included on the ''[[Melody Maker]]'' ''Vinyl Conflict 2'' free EP in September 1986. By the end of the year the lineup had changed again to accommodate the still present figure of Cobalt Stargazer (real name Geoff Bird) and new drummer Slam Thunderhide (real name Stephen Landrum). That lineup contributed the studio track, \"Drug Shoes,\" to the FOOD ''Imminent 2'' various artists compilation.\n\nAt various times, the band has also featured Evil Bastard (real name Robert Munro who co-penned and sang on two [[A-side and B-side|B-sides]]: \"Hangover from Hell\" and \"Lager Woman from Hell\"), Heavy Metal Bear (real name Alex Bradly), Trash D Garbage (real name Paul Bailey), Flash Bastard (real name Jan Cyrka), Suzi X (real name Richard Levy), Tex Diablo (real name Christopher Renshaw), and Robbie Vom (real name Rob Morris).\n\nZodiac Mindwarp progressed rapidly from their first gig at [[Dingwalls]] in November 1985, to playing in front of a packed [[Reading Festival]] in 1986, but was followed by the departure of Kid Chaos who joined [[The Cult]]. Zodiac regrouped by assigning Trash D Garbage on Bass and Flash Bastard (Jan Cyrka) on rhythm guitar section. The expanded five member outfit all went on to record Zodiac Mindwarp and the Love Reaction's debut album in 1988 entitled ''[[Tattooed Beat Messiah]]''.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> Other band members playing bass include Suzi X, Tex Diablo and Kev Reverb; whilst previous drummers were Robbie Vomm and The Apocalypse.\n\nThe act produced a [[UK Singles Chart]] Top 20 hit with the breakthrough [[Gramophone record|record]] \"Prime Mover\",<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> a song that was inspired musically by [[Hawkwind]]'s 1977 track